org.gridgain.grid.cache.datastructures
Interface GridCacheQueue<T>

All Superinterfaces:
Collection<T>, GridMetadataAware, Iterable<T>, Serializable
public interface GridCacheQueue<T>
extends GridMetadataAware, Collection<T>

This interface provides a rich API for working with Data Grid-based distributed queue.

Note that queue is only available in Enterprise Edition.

Functionality

Cache queue provides an access to cache elements using typical queue API. Cache queue also implements Collection interface.

Note that all Collection methods in the queue can throw GridRuntimeException.

Queue can be unbounded or bounded. Capacity of queue can be set when queue will be created and can't be changed later. Here is an example of how create bounded LIFO queue with capacity of 1000 items GridCache.queue(String, GridCacheQueueType, int) 

 GridCacheQueue<String> queue = cache().queue("anyName", LIFO, 1000);
 ...
 queue.add("item");

Queue provides different access to queue elements:

  • GridCacheQueueType.FIFO (default)
  • GridCacheQueueType.LIFO
  • GridCacheQueueType.PRIORITY
For more information about types of queue refer to GridCacheQueueType documentation.

Priority queue provides sorting queue items by priority. Priority in the queue item can be set using annotation GridCacheQueuePriority. Only one field or method can be annotated in queue item class. Annotated field must be int or Integer and annotated method must return int or Integer result. Here is an example of how annotate queue item: 

 private static class PriorityMethodItem {
       // Priority field.
       private final int priority;

       private PriorityMethodItem(int priority) {
           this.priority = priority;
       }

       // Annotated priority method.
       @GridCacheQueuePriority
       int priority() {
           return priority;
       }
   }

Queue items can be placed on one node or distributed through grid nodes (governed by the cache that created that queue). Distributed mode provides only for partitioned cache and it is configured via collocated parameter. If collocated is true all queue items will be placed on one node, else items will be distributed through all grid nodes.

Here is an example of how create unbounded GridCacheQueueType.PRIORITY queue with items distributed through grid topology. GridCache.queue(String, GridCacheQueueType, int) 

 GridCacheQueue<String> queue = cache().queue("anyName", PRIORITY, Integer.MAX_VALUE, false);
 ...
 queue.add("item");

Distributed Cache Queue provides implementation for:

  • blocking,
  • non-blocking,
  • and asynchronous operations.

Creating Distributed Cache Queue

Instance of distributed cache queue can be created by calling one of the following methods:
  • GridCache.queue(String)
  • GridCache.queue(String, GridCacheQueueType)
  • GridCache.queue(String, GridCacheQueueType, int)
  • GridCache.queue(String, GridCacheQueueType, int, boolean)

addAll

boolean addAll(Collection<? extends T> items)
               throws GridRuntimeException
Bulk operation for adding more than one item to queue at once without blocking. Only one internal transaction will be created (as opposed to multiple ones if method GridCacheQueue.add(Object) was called multiple times).

If queue is bounded and does not have enough capacity to add all items, then none of the items will be added and false will be returned.

Specified by:
addAll in interface Collection<T>
Throws:
GridRuntimeException - If operation failed.
Parameters:
items - Items to add.
Returns:
True if items were added, false if queue did not have enough capacity to fit all the items.
